ce:section.ce:para:
We then constructed a quasi-homogenous photocatalytic H2 evolution system composed of Erythrosin B (ErB) as photosensitizer, triethanolamine (TEOA) (15 vol%, pH 7) as sacrificial electron donor, (NH4)2MoS4 as precursor of MoSx catalyst, and CoCl2 as promoter as well as GQDs as homogenous matrix if needed. Control experiments show that the GQDs alone are inactive for catalyzing H2 evolution from ErB-TEOA system, indicating that GQDs are not an efficient cocatalyst for catalyzing H2 evolution reaction (Fig. 2
                     ). When ErB is absent, GQDs/(NH4)2MoS4/TEOA or GQDs/CoCl2/(NH4)2MoS4/TEOA system hardly lead to the formation of MoSx or Co-MoSx catalysts and subsequent H2 evolution, suggesting that GQDs are not an effective photosensitizer for inducing H2 evolution even though GQDs can absorb a small portion of visible light (Fig. 1e) [47]. In addition, no H2 evolves in the absence of TEOA, suggesting that the reduction half-reaction does not occur [36]. Fig. 2 compares H2 evolution activities of different systems to highlight the important synergistic effects of MoSx, Co dopant, and GQDs for achieving high-performance H2 evolution. It has been confirmed that the MoSx catalyst can be facilely generated by in-situ photoreduction of (NH4)2MoS4 in the presence of ErB and efficiently catalyze the subsequent H2 evolution reaction upon visible light irradiation (λ ≥ 420 nm) [36,37]. In our case, in order to further enhance the H2 evolution activity of in-situ generated MoSx catalyst, the most active Co ions as promoter were added into reaction solution leading to a Co doped MoSx catalyst (Co-MoSx) [37,41]. It is clearly that the resulting Co-MoSx (102.7 μmol h−1) shows much superior H2 evolution activity to MoSx catalyst (54.2 μmol h−1). Note that the in-situ generated Co catalyst only shows very low activity (3.2 μmol h−1) for catalyzing H2 evolution from ErB-TEOA system, thus the high activity of Co-MoSx catalyst could be attributable to the effective promotional effect of Co doping, consistent with our previous observations [37,41]. In the presence of GQDs, the activity of the resulted GQDs/Co catalyst (29.4 μmol h−1) could be largely enhanced as compared to Co catalyst alone, while the coupled GQDs/MoSx catalyst (56.0 μmol h−1) only shows slightly higher activity than MoSx catalyst. This could be explained by the fact that the negatively charged GQDs could be an ideal matrix to anchor positively charged Co ions and the in-situ formed Co catalyst could achieve a higher dispersion on GQDs, while the negatively charged MoS4
                     2- ions are not easily accessible to the surfaces of GQDs due to the electrostatic repulsion between them, resulting in a unfavorable coupling for GQDs and in-situ generated MoSx. Most importantly, in the presence of GQDs, the activity of resulted GQDs/Co-MoSx catalyst (179.4 μmol h−1) could be further enhanced as compared to Co-MoSx catalyst, which is also much higher than that of individual GQDs/Co and GQDs/MoSx as well as the sum of their individual H2 evolution activities (85.5 μmol h−1). Note that the GQDs alone show no H2 evolution activity and GQDs/Co, GQDs/MoSx, and Co-MoSx exhibit relatively low activity for H2 evolution, therefore, the strong synergistic effects of MoSx, Co dopant, and GQDs are deduced to be account for the enhanced photocatalytic H2 evolution activity of GQDs/Co-MoSx in ErB-sensitized system, and the detailed mechanism will be discussed below. It should also be mentioned that this ErB-sensitized GQDs/Co-MoSx photocatalytic system are quasi-homogenous before light irradiation, during the H2 evolution reaction, and after reaction (Fig. S3), which enables to study the reaction processes and mechanism of this system using UV–vis absorption spectroscopy and photoluminescence spectroscopy (see below).
